net.automatalib.words.impl

Class SymbolHidingAlphabet<I>

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.automatalib.words.impl.SymbolHidingAlphabet<I>
  • Type Parameters:
    I - input symbol type
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Iterable<I>, Collection<I>, Comparator<I>, IntFunction<I>, ToIntFunction<I>, ArrayWritable<I>, Alphabet<I>, GrowingAlphabet<I>

    public class SymbolHidingAlphabet<I>
extends Object
implements GrowingAlphabet<I>, Serializable
    This alphabet wrapper allows to temporarily hide symbols, so that containment checks (such as Alphabet.containsSymbol(Object)) return false even though the symbol is contained in the wrapped alphabet. Adding the hidden symbol to this alphabet will return the correct return values for the corresponding methods (e.g. its index for GrowingAlphabet.addSymbol(Object)) but not add the symbol to the backing alphabet if the backing alphabet already contained the symbol.

    Note: For now, this only holds for containment checks and add-methods. Other methods, such as Collection.iterator() or Alphabet.getSymbol(int)) access the underlying alphabet directly and do not hide symbols.

    The purpose of this class is to help management of mutable (e.g. growing) alphabets that are shared across several components (automata, learning algorithms) that use the alphabet state to skip redundant work (e.g. allocate memory only for every unique symbol). Since updates to the wrapped alphabet are directly present at the components that hold a reference, additional update-steps of the components may be wrongfully skipped.

    Author:
    frohme
